│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe failure is an assertion from MemorySSA          │
│ verification: a MemoryDef does not dominate its uses. This indicates the CFG  │
│ edits performed during unswitching left MemorySSA in an inconsistent state:   │
│ some MemorySSA def still appears on a path that no longer dominates a use     │
│ (typically a PHI or instruction in successors), or there are                  │
│ duplicated/incorrect incoming edges causing def-use lists to be               │
│ mismatched.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log:\nThe first transformation happens in │
│ SimpleLoopUnswitch::unswitchNontrivialInvariants. The log shows full          │
│ non-trivial unswitching of a branch on %or.cond.i. The crash occurs right     │
│ after unswitchNontrivialInvariants calls verifyMemorySSA the first time       │
│ following the major CFG changes. The relevant code paths show robust          │
│ MemorySSA updates in the FullUnswitch branch: removing duplicate PHI edges,   │
│ updateForClonedLoop, updateExitBlocksForClonedLoop, and removeEdge for        │
│ unswitched successors. However, in the partial-branch unswitch path (the else │
│ case beginning at line ~2459), we perform DT updates and cloning updates, but │
│ do not perform any MemorySSA edge/phi cleanup analogous to the FullUnswitch   │
│ path.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nWhen partially unswitching a branch, the    │
│ code rewrites the terminator in the split block to direct traffic to the      │
│ cloned preheader vs the original preheader. However, unlike FullUnswitch, it  │
│ does not:\n- Remove duplicate incoming edges between ParentBB and             │
│ RetainedSuccBB nor ParentBB and unswitched successors in PHIs via             │
│ MSSAU->removeDuplicatePhiEdgesBetween.\n- Remove now-dead edges from ParentBB │
│ to the unswitched successors via MSSAU->removeEdge.\nWithout these MemorySSA  │
│ updates, the cloned loop phis (and possibly original loop phis) can retain    │
│ duplicate or stale incoming edges. This leads to MemoryDef/Use nodes that no  │
│ longer have proper dominance relative to their uses – exactly the assertion   │
│ reported by MemorySSA::verifyOrderingDominationAndDefUses.\n\nGiven the       │
│ reproducer involves a loop with a single branch (nontrivial unswitching       │
│ condition) and malloc in the body, the MSSA structure is sensitive to PHI     │
